Many of you are very upset about this change, and I understand it's quite a different system that we had, but..
1. having a ton of excess nodes on models causes delays in validation and therefore when instances do go offline we don't catch it as fast meaning it causes problems/delays/etc. when we try to route to the instances, degrading the overall service a fair amount
  - we can optimize this more, and will, but regardless we shouldn't need to validate 1000 nodes if 200 will do the work exactly as well with no degradation and we can iterate much faster and "heal" the cluster faster
2. we've been capping instances for quite some time, but now this cap is extended to all models
3. miners have been often ignoring bounties/cold models, and/or not scaling up chutes getting heavily rate limited, which is their perogative but we need to make sure we serve our customers, particularly developers trying to build on our platform
  - if we don't cap instances, we'll basically never have inventory available to quickly spin up for these new models, for example Affine (const's subnet) needs these models deployed for their subnet to work
4. we really are trying to get jobs out beyond an alpha stage so we can have a dutch auction or similar type of mechanism to make the inventory available for things like model training, fine-tuning, or simple server rentals
  - if we don't cap instances, jobs will rarely run unless we also excessively disproportionately incentivize this specific aspect, which we may have to do anyways

This change addresses all of those things: higher efficiency, incentivizes scaling better, allows hardware to be available when necessary for new models/etc., reduces time between validations to detect down instances faster, etc.

I tried to add the "boost" mechanism, but that didn't actually translate into miners scaling up those chutes much.  I tried drastically increasing the bounty total amount and removed the per version per day limitation so there would be more opportunities to launch these models, etc., but that hasn't really worked either, to a certain extent (e.g. developers regularling pinging me why no miners were even attempting to scale up their newly deployed model).

Since the boosts and bounty changes didn't really work, and jobs weren't really getting picked up, we had to take a heavier-handed approach.

Of course, there are potentially other, better solutions to address all of these problems, but I'm not sure what they could be. If you do have better ideas, aside from "don't cap ever" (because we need all the things outlined above and incentive changes weren't helping) I would love to hear them.

Keep in mind also the base gepetto is just a template, and can be optimized much more than it is today probably. For example, you could subscribe to the events websocket and listen for instance_deleted events cross-referenced to the unscalable chutes and instantly deploy at that time instead of waiting for the autoscale loop, etc.  There is a lot more room for miner optimization now than there was before, in my opinion, and you can be competitive via code and ops rather than purely based on your total inventory, which can allow more diversity of miners.

I have several questions I’d like to discuss:

1. Currently, the maximum allowed number of instances is 5, and some instances may go offline (uncertainty). If one instance goes offline, the failure rate becomes 25%. If the maximum allowed number of instances is 10, then with one offline instance, the failure rate would be 10%. Obviously, the maximum allowed 5 instances seem to have a greater impact on developers. I’m not sure if this understanding is correct.

2. I’m uncertain whether better incentives for scaling can be established. If miners’ GPUs are not utilized for model deployment over a long period of time, I think they will eventually leave, which might result in the platform having fewer GPUs available. When new models require hardware, there might not be GPUs available (the uncertainty of model scaling capability discourages stable GPUs from returning).

3. Monitoring mechanisms for excessive instances are indeed quite troublesome. Too many instances increase the stress on checks, which could lead to delays in kicking out faulty nodes. Is there a quick/simplified mechanism to address this issue? For example, common backend health checks in clusters (such as using ping, port checks, or status codes, etc.).

4. If 200 nodes can complete the work, then of course it’s better to use 200 nodes to complete it. Under the same emissions, miners can achieve the same returns at lower costs—this is agreeable.

5. Bounty tasks/cold models mainly suffer from the lack of computation/calls to continuously maintain node scores. Relying only on a single bounty (which also requires competition) to incentivize miners makes it difficult for them to choose and deploy these models. Increasing bounty tasks for these cold models or providing other incentives might make miners more willing to deploy them (e.g., offering multiple bounties for cold models or providing online rewards for long-term deployment on models with fewer calls).

6. The idea of server leasing is excellent. I think miners don’t really care how the servers are handled—they would 100% entrust the servers to the platform as long as they receive returns.

Additionally, I’m not opposed to any changes being made, as these changes are certainly aimed at moving the platform in a better direction. I’m just raising some thoughts and questions. I sincerely hope chutes can develop stably and efficiently in the long term (I’ve been running chutes for 4 months now, and it is indeed the most widely used platform—not like many projects that are just idle without actual users or traffic). It’s been a long time since I’ve seen such an excellent project.
